{{Hinduism by country}}
'''Hinduism in Malawi''' arrived when Indian laborers were brought by the colonial British administrators in late 19th and early 20th-century in what was then known as British Central Africa and later [[Nyasaland]].<ref name="MittalThursby2009p87"/><ref name="Knott2016p91">{{cite book|author=Kim Knott|title=Hinduism: A Very Short Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Ts6CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA91 |year=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-874554-9|pages=91–92}}</ref> They were a part of a global movement of workers to parts of [[East Africa]], to help build infrastructure projects, establish services, retail markets and for administrative support.<ref name="MittalThursby2009p87">{{cite book|author1=Sushil Mittal|author2=Gene Thursby|title=Studying Hinduism: Key Concepts and Methods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdBFq2Ia79AC&pg=PA87|year=2009|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-41829-9|pages=87–88}}</ref><ref name="Knott2016p91"/><ref>{{cite book|author1=DAVID LEVINSON|author2=KAREN CHRISTENSEN|title=Encyclopedia of Community: From the Village to the Virtual World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t1geOjQ6R0MC&pg=PA592|year=2003|publisher=Sage Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-2598-9|page=592}}</ref> The immigrants, some educated and skilled but mostly poor and struggling in famine prone areas of Punjab, Gujarat, Uttar Pradesh, Bihar and Bengal, helped construct the first railway line between Malawi and Mozambique.<ref name="Knott2016p91"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Frederic L. Pryor|title=Malaŵi and Madagascar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0P0fDzMA5lEC |year=1990|publisher=World Bank|isbn=978-0-19-520823-8|pages=29–34}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Harry Brind|title=Lying Abroad: Diplomatic Memoirs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=06I32BhzaDkC |year=1999|publisher=The Radcliffe Press|isbn=978-1-86064-377-4|pages=189–195}}</ref>

Hinduism has a very small minority presence in predominantly Christian Malawi. The government tracks Christian and Muslim demographics, but does not recognize other religions separately, considers Hindus as well as the traditional African religions as a part of the "Others" category. The "Others" were about 3.1% in 2006.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2006/71311.htm International Religious Freedom Report 2006, Malawi], State Department of the United States</ref><ref>[http://www.ifpri.org/pubs/cp/malawiatlas/malawiatlas_06.pdf Malawi] IFPRI</ref>

According to the 1994 constitution of Malawi, many seats in its Senate are reserved for "major religious faiths of Malawi", and only [[Christianity]] and [[Islam]] is recognized as "major faiths". Malawi thus constitutionally bars people with faiths such as Hinduism from political representation in its Senate, allows only Christians and Muslims to hold the set aside seats of political power.<ref>{{cite book|author=Jeroen Temperman|title=State-Religion Relationships and Human Rights Law: Towards a Right to Religiously Neutral Governance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Khag6tbsIn4C |year=2010|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-18148-2|pages=94–95 with footnote 4–5}}</ref>

After colonialism ended, Hindus (along with Jains and Sikhs) were discriminated against in East Africa, where various East African governments promoted [[Africanization#Africanization of civil services|Africanization]] enacting laws and policies that required commercial and professional sectors of the economy to be owned by non-Europeans, non-Asians, and only indigenous Africans.<ref name="Vertovec2013p87">{{cite book|author=Steven Vertovec|title=The Hindu Diaspora: Comparative Patterns|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRRUAQAAQBAJ |year=2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-136-36712-0|pages=87–89|chapter=Chapter 4}}</ref> Many Hindus previously residing in Malawi migrated to other countries during this period, particularly the [[United Kingdom]] starting with the 1960s.<ref name="MittalThursby2009p87"/>

Gujarati, Sindhi and Bengali are the Main languages of Hindus in Malawi. Sub-traditions of Hinduism such as the [[Brahma Kumaris]] have a Raja Yoga Centre at Trikum Mansion in [[Blantyre]].<ref>[http://www.brahmakumaris.org/afr/malawi/home_html Brahma Kumaris in Malawi], Brahma Kumaris Official Site, Malawi</ref>

